{{multiple issues| {{more footnotes|date=November 2016}} {{original research|date=November 2016}} {{refimprove|date=November 2016}} }} {{Infobox ethnic group | group = | flag = | flag_caption = | image = | ref2 = | languages = [[American English|English]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], [[Korean languages|Korean]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Ilokano language|Ilokano]], other [[Languages of Asia]], [[Spanish language in the United States|Spanish]]<ref name= SpanishChinese >{{cite book|author1=Jonathan H. X. Lee|author2=Kathleen M. Nadeau|title=Encyclopedia of Asian American Folklore and Folklife|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9BrfLWdeISoC&pg=PA334|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-35066-5|pages=333–334|quote=Since the Philippines was colonized by Spain, Filipino Americans in general can speak and understand Spanish too.}}</ref>| religions = [[Protestantism in the United States|Protestantism]], [[Roman Catholicism in the United States|Catholicism]], [[Buddhism in the United States|Buddhism]], [[Hinduism in the United States|Hinduism]], [[Islam in the United States|Islam]], [[Sikhism in the United States|Sikhism]], [[Irreligion in the United States|Irreligion]], [[Religion in the United States|Others]] | related = [[Asian Americans]] | footnotes = }}
Most early [[Asian American|Asian settler]]s to the [[United States]] went to [[Hawaii]]. Most of these early immigrants moved to the islands as laborers to work on the pineapple, coconut, and sugarcane [[Sugar plantations in Hawaii|plantation]]s. These early migrants have tended to stay, although a handful returned to their home countries. There has also been recent immigration to Hawaii from more ethnic Asian groups, including the [[Thai American|Thai]], [[Indonesian American|Indonesian]], and the [[Vietnamese American|Vietnamese]].
==Filipinos== {{Main|Filipinos in Hawaii}}
Filipinos, like most other [[East Asian]] immigrants to Hawaii, worked on the sugar plantations. In [[2010 United States census|2010]], Filipinos surpassed Japanese as the largest ethnic group. At the time of the [[2000 United States census|2000 census]], they were the third largest ethnic group in the islands.
==Japanese== {{Main|Japanese in Hawaii}}
Until 2010, people of Japanese ancestry made up the majority of Hawaii's population. After the breakout of World War II, More than 110,000 Japanese Americans in the mainland U.S., who mostly lived on the West Coast, were forced into internment camps. However, in Hawai'i, where 150,000-plus Japanese Americans composed over one-third of the population, only 1,200 to 1,800 were also interned.<ref>Ogawa, Dennis M. and Fox, Jr., Evarts C. Japanese Americans, from Relocation to Redress. 1991, page 135.</ref>
==Korean== {{Main|Korean immigration to Hawaii}}
Koreans mainly came to [[Hawaii|the islands]] to work on the [[pineapple]] and [[Sugar plantations in Hawaii|sugar plantations]], but a few, including the family of [[Mary Paik Lee]], came to the mainland (usually [[California]]) after experiencing extreme discrimination.
==Chinese== {{Main|Chinese immigration to Hawaii}}
The Chinese discovered the Hawaiian islands in 1778; the same year as English explorer [[James Cook]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}. A few also came to the islands among the crew of James Cook. Today, some Chinese born on the islands can claim to be seventh generation.
==Indians==
People of Indian origin did not come to Hawaii in sizable numbers, and those who did did not stay for long. Many early [[Indian American|Indian immigrants]] stopped in Hawaii only to make enough money to sail on to the mainland anywhere from the mid to late 1800's to the 1900s.
A notable Indian in Hawaii was Dalip Singh Saund, who on September 13, 1910, arrived in [[Honolulu]] from his home village in [[Punjab, British India|Punjab]], [[India]] at the age of 14. He labored in the sugarcane fields for about two months to earn enough money to continue on to California. On November 18, 1910, he arrived on [[United States Immigration Station, Angel Island|Angel Island]]. At one point, Saund was the nation's largest [[celery]] grower.
