{{Infobox language |name=Kerek |states=[[Russia]] |region=[[Chukotka Autonomous Okrug]] |ethnicity=[[Kereks]] |extinct=(3 elderly speakers in 1991) |ref=e18 |familycolor=Paleosiberian |fam1=[[Chukotko-Kamchatkan languages|Chukotko-Kamchatkan]] |fam2=[[Chukotkan languages|Chukotkan]] |iso3=krk |glotto=kere1280 |glottorefname=Kerek }}
'''Kerek''' ({{lang-ru|Керекский язык}}) is an extinct language of [[Russia]] of the northern branch of the [[Chukotko-Kamchatkan languages]]. On historical linguistic grounds it is most closely related to [[Koryak language|Koryak]] (both languages have a [[Phonemic differentiation#Phonemic mergers|merger]] of the proto-Chuktotian [[phonemes]] /*ð/ and /*r/ with /*j/). The next closest relative is Chukchi (/*ð/ and /*r/ are merged, but not /*j/).
In 1997 there were still two speakers remaining, but by 2005 the language was considered extinct.<ref>Fortescue, Michael 2005. ''Comparative Chukotko-Kamchatkan Dictionary''. Berlin / New York: Mouton de Gruyter.</ref> According to the 2010 census,<ref>[http://www.gks.ru/free_doc/new_site/population/demo/per-itog/tab6.xls 2010 census]</ref> there were 10 people claiming Kerek as their native language, a number which may include partial speakers and non-speakers who claim the language as part of their ethnic heritage. Over the 20th century many members of the [[Kereks|Kerek ethnic group]] [[Language shift|shifted]] to [[Chukchi language|Chukchi]], the language of the majority ethnic group in the area, but now most [[Chukchi people|Chukchis]] and [[Kereks]] speak [[Russian language|Russian]].
Kerek is an agglutinative language, meaning that the morphemes build on each other to have different meanings. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lingsib.iea.ras.ru/en/languages/kerek.shtml|title=Endangered Languages of Siberia - The Kerek Language|website=lingsib.iea.ras.ru|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref>
