{{Infobox NRHP | name = Tavern Club | nrhp_type = | image = Tavern Club in Cleveland.jpg | caption = Back of the club | location= 3522 Prospect Ave., [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]] | coordinates = {{coord|41|30|4.9|N|81|39|45.3|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = United States Cleveland#Ohio#USA | built = 1905 | architect = Dyer, J. Milton | architecture = Northern Renaissance | added = November 1, 1984 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | mpsub = {{NRHP url|id=64000653|title=Upper Prospect MRA}} | refnum = 84000235<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> }} The '''Tavern Club''' is a [[gentlemen's club|private social club]] in the [[Central (Cleveland)|Central]] neighborhood of [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], [[United States|USA]]. Its home is a building designed by architect [[J. Milton Dyer]] in a [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Northern Renaissance style]]. It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1984.<ref name=nris/> It was also designated as a landmark by the City of Cleveland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://planning.city.cleveland.oh.us/landmark/listDetail.php?identity=233 |title=Cleveland Designated Landmarks: Property Detail |publisher=Cleveland Landmarks Commission |accessdate=2010-01-16}}</ref>
Dyer was a member of the Tavern Club, which was established 1892-93. He designed a building for the group when it moved from a leased property at 968 Prospect Street to its present building on January 1, 1905. "The exterior construction and the traditional interior decor of the building" have remained essentially the same since the club's beginning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ech.cwru.edu/ech-cgi/article.pl?id=TC |title=Tavern Club |work=The Encyclopedia of Cleveland History |publisher=[[Case Western Reserve University]] |date=1997-07-22 |accessdate=2010-01-16}}</ref>
The upstairs originally contained two squash courts and a [[Rackets (sport)|rackets]] court.
